# The committed sample dataset (docs/samples/, DATA-SPEC §9.5) is compared
# byte-for-byte against a fresh build by the I16 drift guard, so what Git does
# to those bytes on checkout has to match what the builder writes.
#
# Two producers, two rules:
#
#   *_results.csv / *_trials.csv come from `csv.writer`, which terminates rows
#   with a literal CRLF on every platform (RFC 4180). Those bytes are in the
#   blob already, so a Windows checkout under core.autocrlf=true — the GitHub
#   runner default — would smudge each LF again and hand the guard \r\r\n.
#   Pinned below.
#
#   Everything else under docs/samples/ (the .json and .md snapshots, and
#   lab-03/bart_export.csv, a hand-written foreign-format fixture) is written
#   through Python text mode, which emits the platform's own line ending. Those
#   must stay ordinary text so the checkout matches the machine running the
#   guard — pinning them would freeze LF against a CRLF build and fail.
docs/samples/**/*_results.csv -text
docs/samples/**/*_trials.csv -text
